"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720716","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-26","<p>The number of staff employed by the secretary of State for Justice’s Department who are a) full-time permanent 52,939, b) part-time permanent 12,353, c) for less than two years’ duration 852, d) on an agency basis 1,829, e) zero-hours contract 18.</p><p>The proportion of staff employed by the Secretary of State for Justice’s department is a) 79.6%, b)18.6%, c) 1.3%, d) 2.7%, e)0.03%</p><p>The proportions have been calculated using headcount of total number of employees. Not all business units have headcount figures available for agency staff for figure is Full time equivalent (FTE). The figures for zero hours contracts are all for HMCS/HMCTS. These staff work as scheduled ushers and do not work fixed hours, being called on as and when required.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720716/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-26T17:58:20.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720716/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720716/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-04-13","Ministry of Justice: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many and what proportion of staff employed by her Department are employed on a contract which is (a) full-time permanent, (b) part-time permanent, (c) for less than two years' duration, (d) on an agency basis and (e) zero-hours.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","70469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720718","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-20","<p>The information requested could only be obtained at a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Jury service is an important civic duty. HMCTS is committed to offering support to those called as jurors. Financial provision is made for jurors who are on benefits and for those who suffer loss of earning whilst on jury service. Full details of that provision can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/jury-service/what-you-can-claim" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/jury-service/what-you-can-claim</a></p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720718/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T15:02:09.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720718/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720718/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-04-13","Juries: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate she has made of the level of lost earnings incurred by (a) employees and (b) the self-employed undertaking jury service by income decile in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","70411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720719","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Secretary of State for Justice has not met with any organisations to discuss issues related to anti-Semitism since 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Details of Ministers' meetings with external organisations are published routinely on Gov.uk and can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/moj-gifts-hospitality-travel-and-meetings" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/moj-gifts-hospitality-travel-and-meetings</a>.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720719/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-25T16:33:08.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720719/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720719/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-04-13","Antisemitism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many meetings she has had with which organisations to discuss issues related to anti-Semitism since 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","70429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720720","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-20","<p>The email enquiry from the hon. Member for Glasgow East on behalf of a constituent on 20 February 2017 was answered on Wednesday 19 April 2017.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720720/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T13:14:48.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720720/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720720/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-04-13","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the email of 20 March 2017, when she plans to respond to the email enquiry from the hon. Member for Glasgow East on behalf of a constituent on 20 February 2017.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","70662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720723","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-24","<p>I would refer the Honourable Member to the reply I gave on 29 March.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720723/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T10:56:04.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720723/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720723/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-04-13","Prisons: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will introduce guidance for prison authorities on safe staffing levels setting out a specific prisoner to staff ratio required per shift; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","70692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720724","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-25","<p>The department’s progress in identifying and selling surplus land for housing is set out in the Public Land for Housing Programme Annual Report published in February 2017.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/592919/170124_PSL_Annual_Report_FINAL_for_publication.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/592919/170124_PSL_Annual_Report_FINAL_for_publication.pdf</a></p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720724/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-25T14:08:47.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720724/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720724/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-04-13","Ministry of Justice: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to paragraphs 1.296 and 1.297 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, what progress her Department has made by estimated capacity of land sold since March 2016 in identifying and disposing of land to meet the Government's commitment.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Prisk","Hertford and Stortford","Mr Mark Prisk","70683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720725","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-24","<p>As I said in my reply to the hon. gentleman’s earlier question answered on the 28 March, the Government has not made an assessment of the use of voice recorders or body cameras for bailiffs.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720725/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T14:59:40.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720725/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720725/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-04-13","Debt Collection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 28 March 2017 to Question 68373, if she will make it her policy to mandate the use of voice recorders or body cameras for (a) bailiffs carrying out enforcement activity for public bodies and (b) other bailiffs.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","70482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720726","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Prisons and Probation Ombudsman does not have a publicly appointed Board. The Ombudsman is the only public appointee. The current Ombudsman, Nigel Newcomen, was appointed in September 2011 for a period of five years. His tenure has been extended until July 2017 and the recruitment process for his successor is underway. An Advisory Assessment Panel will assess candidates and then ministers will put forward a preferred candidate for pre-appointment scrutiny by the Justice Select Committee prior to announcement.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720726/answer",,,,,"70561 ; 70725","2017-04-24T10:11:19.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720726/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720726/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-04-13","Prisons and Probation Ombudsman","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many applications the board of the Prison and Probation Ombudsman received during its last intake.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720727","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-24","<p>Information on the Ministry of Justice procurement spending relating to the services of management consultants is set out in our annual report for each year. These reports can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications</a> listed under Spend on Consultancy.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720727/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T15:01:20.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720727/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720727/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-04-13","Ministry of Justice: Management Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 27 February 2017 to Question 65691, how much of the procurement spending in each year since 2010 related to the services of management consultants.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70528"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720728","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-04-21","<p>The maximum penalties for animal welfare offences are kept under review and Defra is in regular discussion with the Ministry of Justice on appropriate sentencing levels. The Sentencing Council recently published revised magistrates’ court sentencing guidelines with the aim of ensuring that the most serious cases of animal cruelty receive appropriately severe penalties within the available maximum penalty.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720728/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-21T13:28:44.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720728/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720728/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-04-13","Animal Welfare: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether her Department plans to increase the maximum custodial sentence for the most serious acts of animal cruelty to five years imprisonment in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Sammy Wilson","East Antrim","Sammy Wilson","70540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720730","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Prisons and Probation Ombudsman does not have a publicly appointed Board. The Ombudsman is the only public appointee. The current Ombudsman, Nigel Newcomen, was appointed in September 2011 for a period of five years. His tenure has been extended until July 2017 and the recruitment process for his successor is underway. An Advisory Assessment Panel will assess candidates and then ministers will put forward a preferred candidate for pre-appointment scrutiny by the Justice Select Committee prior to announcement.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720730/answer",,,,,"70477 ; 70725","2017-04-24T10:11:19.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720730/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720730/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-04-13","Prisons and Probation Ombudsman","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, who is involved with board appointments for the Prison and Probation Ombudsman; at what stage each of those people are involved; and whether each person advises or decides on appointments.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720732","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-24","<p>The government has now submitted its evidence to the Prison Service Pay Review Body (PSPRB), which outlines the pay proposals for all operational prison staff for 2017/18, following extensive talks with both the Prison Officers’ Association (POA) and the Prison Governors’ Association (PGA).</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720732/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T10:26:12.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720732/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720732/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-04-13","Prison Officers: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether she has submitted evidence to the Prison Officers Pay Review Body; and what the reasons were for the time taken for that submission.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","70588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720734","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Department does not have a specific budget for procurement management as the cost of this task is subsumed within existing corporate service roles and therefore not separately identified.</p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720734/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T10:35:00.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720734/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720734/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-04-13","Northern Ireland Office: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, pursuant to the Answer of 1 March 2017 to Question 65004, on procurement,  what estimate he has made of the total budget for procurement management in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720735","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>Under the Parliamentary Constituencies Act 1986 the deputy chair of the Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland must be a High Court judge appointed by the Lord Chief Justice for Northern Ireland. The Commission also has two members who are appointed by the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland. The appointment of members is regulated by the Office of the Commissioner for Public Appointments (OCPA) and is carried out in line with the Governance Code for Public Appointments:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/578498/governance_code_on_public_appointments_16_12_2016.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/578498/governance_code_on_public_appointments_16_12_2016.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The last OCPA regulated process to recruit a member of the Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland was completed in December 2015. The selection panel for this competition considered 21 applications.</p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720735/answer",,,,,"70724 ; 70864","2017-04-24T10:40:30.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720735/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720735/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-04-13","Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many applications the board of the Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland received during its last intake.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720736","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Department does not own any land.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720736/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T10:36:04.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720736/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720736/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-04-13","Northern Ireland Office: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, with reference to paragraphs 1.296 and 1.297 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, what progress his Department has made by estimated capacity of land sold since March 2016 in identifying and disposing of land to meet the Government's commitment.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Prisk","Hertford and Stortford","Mr Mark Prisk","70684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720737","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>As of February 2017, the latest date for which data is available, the number and proportion of staff employed by the Department is as follows:</p><p> </p><p>a) Full- time permanent - 63 (78%);</p><p>b) Part-time permanent - 5 (6%);</p><p>c) Contract of less than 2 years - 1 (1%) (Apprentice on a 18-month contract);</p><p>d) Agency staff - 5 (6%);</p><p>e) Zero hours contract - 0.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720737/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T10:38:16.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720737/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720737/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-04-13","Northern Ireland Office: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many and what proportion of staff employed by his Department are employed on a contract which is (a) full-time permanent, (b) part-time permanent, (c) for less than two years' duration, (d) on an agency basis and (e) zero-hours.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","70470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720738","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>None of the spending on external contracts was for the services of management consultants.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720738/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T10:32:49.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720738/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720738/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-04-13","Northern Ireland Office: Management Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, pursuant to the Answer of 28 February 2017 to Question 64400, how much of the spending on external contracts was for the services of management consultants in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720739","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>As of February 2017, the latest date for which data is available, there are 30 staff seconded to the department from the Northern Ireland Civil Service.</p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720739/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T10:30:52.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720739/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720739/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-04-13","Northern Ireland Office: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many staff are seconded to his Department; and how many such staff are seconded from which companies and organisations.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","70956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720740","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>Under the Parliamentary Constituencies Act 1986 the deputy chair of the Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland must be a High Court judge appointed by the Lord Chief Justice for Northern Ireland. The Commission also has two members who are appointed by the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland. The appointment of members is regulated by the Office of the Commissioner for Public Appointments (OCPA) and is carried out in line with the Governance Code for Public Appointments:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/578498/governance_code_on_public_appointments_16_12_2016.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/578498/governance_code_on_public_appointments_16_12_2016.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The last OCPA regulated process to recruit a member of the Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland was completed in December 2015. The selection panel for this competition considered 21 applications.</p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720740/answer",,,,,"70485 ; 70724","2017-04-24T10:40:30.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720740/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720740/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-04-13","Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, who makes appointments to the Board of the Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland; which other organisations or individuals provide advice on those appointments; and at what stage of the process they each do so.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720741","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>Under the Parliamentary Constituencies Act 1986 the deputy chair of the Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland must be a High Court judge appointed by the Lord Chief Justice for Northern Ireland. The Commission also has two members who are appointed by the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland. The appointment of members is regulated by the Office of the Commissioner for Public Appointments (OCPA) and is carried out in line with the Governance Code for Public Appointments:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/578498/governance_code_on_public_appointments_16_12_2016.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/578498/governance_code_on_public_appointments_16_12_2016.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The last OCPA regulated process to recruit a member of the Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland was completed in December 2015. The selection panel for this competition considered 21 applications.</p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720741/answer",,,,,"70485 ; 70864","2017-04-24T10:40:30.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720741/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720741/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-04-13","Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what proportion of the Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland board are (a) women, (b) from black or minority ethnic backgrounds, (c) disabled or (d) from lower socio-economic backgrounds.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720742","Cabinet Office","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is an integral part of the Cabinet Office and is included in this reply.</p><p> </p><p>As March 2017, Cabinet Office had 36 staff seconded in from outside of the Civil Service. Full details of the companies and organisations that staff are seconded from are not held centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720742/answer",,,,,"70942","2017-04-25T15:05:54.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720742/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720742/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-04-13","Prime Minister: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many staff are employed by 10 Downing Street on a seconded basis; and how many such staff are seconded from which companies and organisations.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","70984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720743","Prime Minister","false","2017-04-20","<p>Anti-Semitism continues to be a problem in this country which is why it is right that, as a Government, we are able to demonstrate the seriousness with which we take it, as we do for other forms of hate crime.</p><p>This Government has led the way in adopting the International Holocaust Remembrance Alliance working definition of anti-Semitism and continues to build on the solid work of the cross-Government working group on tackling anti-Semitism, which ensures that we are alive to any issues and concerns of the Jewish community and can respond quickly. I and ministerial colleagues are in regular contact with representatives of the Jewish community, including the Jewish Leadership Council, the Board of Deputies of British Jews, the Community Security Trust and other key stakeholders. Concerns about the levels of anti-Semitism and anti-Semitism on the internet are discussed by the relevant Cabinet ministers as and when the need arises, and with international counterparts.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720743/answer",,,,,"70457","2017-04-20T12:04:22.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720743/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720743/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-04-13","Antisemitism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, how many meetings she has had and with whom at which anti-Semitism was discussed.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","70456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720744","Prime Minister","false","2017-04-20","<p>Anti-Semitism continues to be a problem in this country which is why it is right that, as a Government, we are able to demonstrate the seriousness with which we take it, as we do for other forms of hate crime.</p><p>This Government has led the way in adopting the International Holocaust Remembrance Alliance working definition of anti-Semitism and continues to build on the solid work of the cross-Government working group on tackling anti-Semitism, which ensures that we are alive to any issues and concerns of the Jewish community and can respond quickly. I and ministerial colleagues are in regular contact with representatives of the Jewish community, including the Jewish Leadership Council, the Board of Deputies of British Jews, the Community Security Trust and other key stakeholders. Concerns about the levels of anti-Semitism and anti-Semitism on the internet are discussed by the relevant Cabinet ministers as and when the need arises, and with international counterparts.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720744/answer",,,,,"70456","2017-04-20T12:04:24.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720744/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720744/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-04-13","Antisemitism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, how many times she has discussed (a) anti-Semitism and (b) anti-Semitism on the internet with her (i) Cabinet colleagues and (ii) international counterparts.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","70457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720745","Scotland Office","false","2017-04-20","<p>The Scotland Office does not employ staff directly.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720745/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T11:00:39.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720745/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720745/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-04-13","Scotland Office: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many and what proportion of staff employed by his Department are employed on a contract which is (a) full-time permanent, (b) part-time permanent, (c) for less than two years' duration, (d) on an agency basis and (e) zero-hours.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","70471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720746","Scotland Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>I have regular discussions with Cabinet colleagues on a range of issues. I fully support the Time for Inclusive Education campaign to tackle prejudice and spread understanding in our schools, giving LGBTI young people equality and respect.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720746/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T09:44:28.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720746/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720746/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-04-13","Schools: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what discussions he has had with his Cabinet colleagues on the Time for Inclusive Education campaign.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","70267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720747","Scotland Office","false","2017-04-20","<p>The press and engagement team of the Scotland Office have access to the Scotland Office’s digital platforms. The team consists of ten people.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720747/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T11:08:35.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720747/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720747/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-04-13","Scotland Office: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many of the staff in his Department have access to his Department's official (a) Twitter and (b) Facebook account.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","70266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720748","Scotland Office","false","2017-04-20","<p>The Scotland Office does not own any land and has not done so since its creation in 1999.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720748/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T11:01:45.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720748/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720748/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-04-13","Scotland Office: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, with reference to paragraphs 1.296 and 1.297 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, what progress his Department has made by estimated capacity of land sold since March 2016 in identifying and disposing of land to meet the Government's commitment.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Prisk","Hertford and Stortford","Mr Mark Prisk","70685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720749","Scotland Office","false","2017-04-20","<p>Digital activity, including social media campaigns, are funded through the Scotland Office programme budget. This is published in the annual report and accounts, a link to which can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/annual-report-and-accounts-2015-16--2" target="_blank"><strong>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/annual-report-and-accounts-2015-16--2</strong></a></p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720749/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T10:59:22.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720749/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720749/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-04-13","Scotland Office: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how much his Department has spent on promoting social media post in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","70655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720750","Scotland Office","false","2017-04-20","<p>Social media posts across Twitter and Facebook are accessible from anywhere by any audience.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720750/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T10:58:20.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720750/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720750/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-04-13","Scotland Office: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, which social media posts from his Department have been promoted in Scotland only.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","70656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720751","Scotland Office","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Boundary Commission for Scotland (BCS) is an advisory, non-departmental public body, sponsored by the Scotland Office. Details of the current members of the BCS can be viewed at this link:</p><p><a href="http://www.bcomm-scotland.independent.gov.uk/commission/commissioners.asp" target="_blank">http://www.bcomm-scotland.independent.gov.uk/commission/commissioners.asp</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The BCS’ two Commissioners are appointed by the Secretary of State for Scotland, in line with the Governance Code for Public Appointments:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/578498/governance_code_on_public_appointments_16_12_2016.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/578498/governance_code_on_public_appointments_16_12_2016.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The most recent appointment to the BCS was made by the Secretary of State for Scotland in February 2016. The successful candidate, Professor Henderson, was selected from a field of 120 applicants, following advertisement in the national press and interview by a panel.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720751/answer",,,,,"70723 ; 70868","2017-04-24T09:47:34.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720751/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720751/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-04-13","Boundary Commission for Scotland: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many applications the board of the Boundary Commission for Scotland received during its last intake.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720752","Scotland Office","false","2017-04-20","<p>The Scotland Office does not employ staff directly. Staff that join do so on assignment or loan/secondment from other government bodies, principally the Ministry of Justice and the Scottish Government.</p><p> </p><p>The office can on occasions employ staff on secondment from non-civil service organisations. As the number of non-civil service secondments is less than 5, detailed information is not provided for privacy reasons.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720752/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T11:03:07.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720752/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720752/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-04-13","Scotland Office: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many staff are seconded to his Department; and how many such staff are seconded from which companies and organisations.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","70957"
