"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720892","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-20","<p>The Director of Labour Market Enforcement (The Director) was appointed on 1 January 2017 and has submitted to ministers an introductory labour market enforcement strategy. In preparing the strategy the Director held stakeholder roundtables, a stakeholder survey, and met with the three enforcement bodies - the Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority, the Employment Agency Standards Inspectorate, and HMRC’s National Minimum Wage team – as well as public bodies and external stakeholders.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720892/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T13:36:51.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720892/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720892/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Migrant Workers: Enforcement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how the Director of Labour Market Enforcement plans to consult before drafting his labour market enforcement strategy.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","70988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720893","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Government does not routinely collect information on the take-up of Shared Parental Leave and Maternity Leave, including by constituent regions.</p><p> </p><p>Maternity Leave is a ‘day 1 right’ and, subject to giving the correct notice, all employed mothers are able to take up to 52 weeks of Maternity Leave and must take at least two weeks of leave immediately following the birth of their child, four weeks if they work in a factory or workshop.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720893/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T14:35:12.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720893/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720893/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Parental Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what comparative assessment he has made of the uptake of shared parental leave and maternity leave in each constituent region of the UK in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mr Gavin Shuker","Luton South","Mr Gavin Shuker","70978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720894","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-20","<p>Where a national minimum wage or national living wage complaint is received by telephone, the Acas adviser establishes the caller’s name and brief details of the issue. These are communicated to HM Revenue and Customs before the call is handed over. Where HMRC do not have an adviser available – for example when all of their advisers are on other calls or the call was made outside of HMRC opening hours – the caller is given an option by the Acas Adviser of leaving a voicemail message with HM Revenue and Customs or ringing Acas back at another time when the call can be transferred.</p><p> </p><p>Since January 2017, callers have the option of using the updated online complaint form on GOV.UK.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720894/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T13:51:37.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720894/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720894/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what procedure ACAS follows in referring to HM Revenue and Customs cases of non-payment of the national minimum wage and national living wage.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","70316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720895","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-20","<p>For the period April 2016-March 2017, management information shows that Acas referred 2,311 calls to HM Revenue and Customs. This figure also includes onward referrals made by Acas Helpline advisers in response to issues raised on the online form on GOV.UK.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Month / Year</p></td><td><p>Referrals</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2016</p></td><td><p>224</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May 2016</p></td><td><p>213</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>June 2016</p></td><td><p>187</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July 2016</p></td><td><p>190</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>August 2016</p></td><td><p>189</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September 2016</p></td><td><p>189</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October 2016</p></td><td><p>180</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>November 2016</p></td><td><p>195</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>December 2016</p></td><td><p>124</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 2017</p></td><td><p>187</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>February 2017</p></td><td><p>220</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>March 2017</p></td><td><p>213</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720895/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T13:54:24.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720895/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720895/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many cases of failure to pay wages ACAS referred to HM Revenue and Customs in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","70317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720896","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-25","<p>This is a matter for the Inquiry led by Steve Holliday that I announced on 27 March 2017.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720896/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-25T12:48:32.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720896/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720896/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Nuclear Decommissioning Authority: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the oral contribution of 27 March 2017, Official Report, column 25, on Magnex: early contract terminations, for what reasons the mismatch referred to was not foreseen by the Nuclear Decommissioning Board when drafting the contract as tendered in 2012.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","70306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720898","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-25","<p>This is a matter for the Inquiry led by Steve Holliday that I announced on 27 March 2017.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720898/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-25T12:50:51.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720898/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720898/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Nuclear Decommissioning Authority: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the oral contribution of 27 March 2017, Official Report, columns 25 to 27, on Magnex: early contract terminations, whether the investigation will include an investigation into the conduct of people involved in the procurement process referred to in Energysolutions EU Ltd v Nuclear Decommissioning Authority [2016] EWHC 1988 (TCC) and in the period following that process.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","70307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720899","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-25","<p>This decision was made by the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority and was a consequence of settling the EnergySolutions case.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720899/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-25T12:57:13.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720899/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720899/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Nuclear Decommissioning Authority: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the reason was for the time taken to make the decision to withdraw the appeal of Energysolutions EU Ltd v Nuclear Decommissioning Authority [2016] EWHC 1988 (TCC).","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","70308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720900","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-25","<p>The former Chairman of the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority, Stephen Henwood, stepped down as planned on 28 February 2017 after having served nine years in the role. John Clarke, former Chief Executive of the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority, announced his retirement on 5 August 2016 and remained in post subsequently to help manage the transition to his successor, who was appointed on 1 March 2017.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720900/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-25T13:00:16.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720900/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720900/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Nuclear Decommissioning Authority: Termination of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, for what reasons the employment contract of the previous Chair and Chief Executive of the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority was terminated; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","70309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720901","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-25","<p>The decision to appeal was made by the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority (NDA) after careful consideration of the adverse High Court judgment of 29 July. The NDA kept the Government informed about the ongoing litigation in the usual way, in line with its Framework Document.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720901/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-25T13:05:33.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720901/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720901/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Nuclear Decommissioning Authority: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, on what grounds the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority decided to appeal the decision Energysolutions EU Ltd v Nuclear Decommissioning Authority [2016] EWHC 1988 (TCC); and whether that decision was formally directed or sanctioned by the Government.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","70310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720902","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-25","<p>This decision was made by the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority (NDA) and was a consequence of settling the EnergySolutions case. The NDA decided to settle as the costs – ultimately borne by the taxpayer – had the potential to rise much further had the case gone to trial. This decision was made with my consent as well as that of the Chief Secretary to the Treasury and the BEIS Accounting Officer.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720902/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-25T13:02:17.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720902/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720902/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Nuclear Decommissioning Authority: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, on what grounds the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority decided to withdraw its appeal of Energysolutions EU Ltd v Nuclear Decommissioning Authority [2016] EWHC 1988 (TCC); and whether that decision was formally directed or sanctioned by the Government.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","70311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720903","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Government is committed to negotiating a deep and special partnership with the European Union to get the very best deal for businesses and households. We want a bold and ambitious free trade agreement, greater in scope than any before it, that allows British companies the maximum freedom to trade with and operate within EU markets, and that lets European business do the same in Britain. The government is conducting a wide-ranging programme of analysis and as we move into the period of negotiation, we have been clear that we will not disclose any material at a time that could affect the UK’s position in those negotiations.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720903/answer",,,,,"70255","2017-04-26T15:59:23.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720903/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720903/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-04-13","Business: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on the economy of business relocating their offices to EU member states following the UK's exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","70254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720904","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-04-26","<p>The Government is committed to negotiating a deep and special partnership with the European Union to get the very best deal for businesses and households. We want a bold and ambitious free trade agreement, greater in scope than any before it, that allows British companies the maximum freedom to trade with and operate within EU markets, and that lets European business do the same in Britain. The government is conducting a wide-ranging programme of analysis and as we move into the period of negotiation, we have been clear that we will not disclose any material at a time that could affect the UK’s position in those negotiations.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720904/answer",,,,,"70254","2017-04-26T15:59:23.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720904/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720904/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-04-13","Business: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on the economy of businesses establishing new subsidiaries within EU member states following the UK's exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","70255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720905","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-24","<p>As part of its work to inform the government’s negotiating position, HM Treasury is engaging with a range of firms from across the financial services sector – including Lloyd’s of London – to understand their plans following the UK’s withdrawal from the EU.</p><p> </p><p>Lloyd’s estimates that the number of jobs moved will be “in the tens, not the hundreds”. The Government is confident that London will remain the world’s preeminent insurance centre.</p><p> </p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720905/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T15:47:25.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720905/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720905/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-04-13","Lloyds of London: Belgium","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on the economy of Lloyds of London establishing a new subsidiary in Brussels following the UK's exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","70257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720906","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>1,015 licensed insolvency practitioners are registered to use the online Director Conduct Reporting Service.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720906/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T11:13:28.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720906/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720906/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Directors: Conduct","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many insolvency practitioners are registered to use the online Director Conduct Reporting Service.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","70258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720907","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-20","<p>Under the Energy Act 2008 my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State has powers to amend electricity and gas supply licences for the purposes of smart metering until 1 November 2018. We published for pre-legislative scrutiny in 2016 two measures related to smart meters including a proposal to extend these powers by five years. This would allow Government to continue to oversee the successful completion of the rollout by the end of 2020 and post-implementation to ensure the ongoing effectiveness of the smart metering policy framework. We are proposing to introduce these measures when parliamentary time allows.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720907/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T13:19:13.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720907/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720907/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans he has to renew smart metering licences due to expire in November 2018 under the Energy Act 2008.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","70235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720908","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-19","<p>The Department intends to conduct a review of the balance of deployment caps between and within technologies, taking into account deployment patterns and wider government priorities. This will be published later this year and include estimates of the Levy Control Framework spend and underspend in the capped Feed-in Tariff budget for all scheme technologies.</p><p>The scheme administrator, Ofgem E-Serve, publishes information on deployment compared to cap levels. This is available <a href="https://www.ofgem.gov.uk/environmental-programmes/fit/contacts-guidance-and-resources/public-reports-and-data-fit/feed-tariffs-deployment-caps-reports" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720908/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-19T14:32:19.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720908/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720908/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Solar Power: Feed-in Tariffs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much Levy Control Framework funding has been allocated to new solar photovoltaic projects awarded a Feed-in Tariff in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","70236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720909","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-19","<p>The Department intends to conduct a review of the balance of deployment caps between and within technologies, taking into account deployment patterns and wider government priorities. This will be published later this year and include estimates of the Levy Control Framework spend and underspend in the capped Feed-in Tariff budget for all scheme technologies.</p><p>The scheme administrator, Ofgem E-Serve, publishes information on deployment compared to cap levels. This is available <a href="https://www.ofgem.gov.uk/environmental-programmes/fit/contacts-guidance-and-resources/public-reports-and-data-fit/feed-tariffs-deployment-caps-reports" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720909/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-19T15:52:09.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720909/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720909/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Renewable Energy: Feed-in Tariffs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what his Department's most recent estimate is of the underspend in the capped Feed-in Tariff budget for new solar photovoltaic and wind projects in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","70237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720910","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-21","<p>The Department requested stakeholders’ views on how we can deploy electricity generation through competitive markets without the requirement for ongoing subsidy as part of our Industrial Strategy Consultation. The Consultation closed on 17 April 2017 and we are considering the responses received.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720910/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-21T10:06:35.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720910/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720910/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what progress he has made on proposals to run subsidy-free auction rounds for solar photovoltaic and onshore wind.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","70238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720911","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>We have now received the report produced by the Working Group on Product Recalls and Safety which was set up by the Department to develop options to improve the safety of white goods and the recall system. We are considering the recommendations made by the Group, and are continuing to engage with them on their progress on activity aimed at improving the recall process. We expect to publish the report on the Product Safety page of gov.uk in due course and will place a copy in the Libraries of both Houses.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720911/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T11:13:43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720911/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720911/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Product Recalls and Safety Working Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when he expects the final report of the Working Group on Product Recalls and Safety to be published; and if he will place a copy of that report in the Library.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","70328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720912","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Department does not hold this information centrally and it can only be provided at disproportional cost. However, we can provide details of spending managing procurement in the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills via UK SBS as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong><em>2013/14</em></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>2014/15</em></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>2015/16</em></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>2016/17</em></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Managing procurement spend (£m)</p></td><td><p>5.9</p></td><td><p>6.3</p></td><td><p>3.9</p></td><td><p>3.7</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720912/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T11:13:59.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720912/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720912/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate his Department has made of its spending on managing procurement since it was established; and what estimate has been made of such spending in each year since 2010 of the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720913","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-25","<p>This Government wants the UK to be the go-to place for innovators and investors across the world, and we intend to secure the best possible outcome for the UK research base as we exit the European Union.</p><p>The United Kingdom’s exit from and new partnership with the European Union’ White Paper set out that the UK Government would welcome an agreement to continue to collaborate with our European partners on major science, research, and technology initiatives and we will approach the upcoming negotiations on this basis. The Government is committed to ensuring the UK remains a world leader in international research and innovation.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720913/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-25T10:16:03.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720913/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720913/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Horizon 2020","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what representations he has made to his EU counterparts on the UK continuing to participate in the Horizon research network after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","70365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720914","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-20","<p>The government is in continuing discussions with the European Commission on securing the remaining exemptions for energy intensive industries. The intention is to introduce the exemptions once the necessary clearances have been secured. The current compensation for the indirect cost of the Renewables Obligation (RO) and small-scale Feed-in Tariffs (FIT) will remain in place in the meantime.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720914/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T16:32:17.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720914/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720914/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Energy Intensive Industries: Trade Competitiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 15 December 2016 to Question 57227, on energy intensive industries: trade competitiveness, by what date his Department plans to introduce the exemption for energy intensive industries.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","70405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720915","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-20","<p>The government is in continuing discussions with the European Commission on securing the remaining exemptions for energy intensive industries. Sufficient funding is in place to continue the current compensation for the indirect cost of the Renewables Obligation (RO) and small-scale Feed-in Tariffs (FIT).</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720915/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T16:33:05.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720915/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720915/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Energy Intensive Industries: Trade Competitiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 15 December 2016 to Question 57226, on energy intensive industries: trade competitiveness, how much additional contingency funding has been allocated to the continuation of compensation for the indirect costs of the Renewables Obligation and small-scale Feed-in Tariffs for energy intensive industries beyond 1 April 2017.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","70406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720916","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Government is committed to supporting economic growth across Scotland and is working with the Scottish Government and local partners to negotiate tailored City Deals with Edinburgh, Stirling and the Tay Cities. These will build on the existing deals we have already agreed for Glasgow, Inverness and Aberdeen – which will unlock up to £701 million of new UK Government funding, subject to agreed business cases for particular projects.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720916/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T08:44:21.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720916/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720916/answer","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720916/answer/previousversion/44893","Biography information for Margot James","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Local Growth Deals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 21 March 2017 to Question 68255, on local growth deals, what funds are available for allocation to regional growth deals in addition to such funding for city deals.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","70407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720917","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-20","<p>Research and development is a key driver of economic growth and is a vital part of the government's Industrial Strategy. The government clearly demonstrated its commitment to science and research in the 2016 Autumn Statement, committing an additional £4.7 billion to R&amp;D funding covering both science and innovation over the period 2017/18 to 20/21. This equates to an extra £2 billion a year by 2020/21, the biggest increase in any parliament since 1979.</p><p>Total R&amp;D expenditure in the UK in 2015 represented 1.68% of Gross Domestic Product (GDP). The rate in future years will depend on both public sector and private sector investment in R&amp;D as well as on the level of GDP.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720917/answer",,,,,"70409","2017-04-20T15:59:26.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720917/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720917/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Research: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of government investment in research and development as a proportion of GDP in (a) 2018-19, (b) 2019-20 and (c) 2020-21.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","70408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720918","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-20","<p>Research and development is a key driver of economic growth and is a vital part of the government's Industrial Strategy. The government clearly demonstrated its commitment to science and research in the 2016 Autumn Statement, committing an additional £4.7 billion to R&amp;D funding covering both science and innovation over the period 2017/18 to 20/21. This equates to an extra £2 billion a year by 2020/21, the biggest increase in any parliament since 1979.</p><p>Total R&amp;D expenditure in the UK in 2015 represented 1.68% of Gross Domestic Product (GDP). The rate in future years will depend on both public sector and private sector investment in R&amp;D as well as on the level of GDP.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720918/answer",,,,,"70408","2017-04-20T15:59:25.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720918/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720918/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Research: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the Government's policy is on increasing its investment in research and development as a proportion of GDP above the OECD average by 2020-21.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","70409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720919","Home Office","false","2017-04-26","<p>Modern slavery can occur in all sectors of business or industry. We are determined to reduce the risk of worker exploitation in all sectors. That is why we have appointed a Director of Labour Market Enforcement. The Director will advise the Government on the threat and how best to counter it. All businesses must stay vigilant to prevent modern slavery and other forms of worker exploitation in their supply chains.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720919/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-26T09:29:30.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720919/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720919/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-04-13","Distributive Trade: Employment Agencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make an assessment of the effect on the prevalence of modern slavery of the use of third party agencies to supply temporary workers in the retail and distribution sectors.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","70450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720920","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-20","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to the hon. Member for Newcastle upon Tyne Central (Chi Onwurah) on 23 February 2017 to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-02-20/64508/" target="_blank">64508</a>.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720920/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T13:34:07.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720920/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720920/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect the current interoperability of SMETS1s will have on consumers' freedom to switch energy suppliers.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","70616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720921","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-20","<p>As of December 2016 there were approximately 0.33 million smart meters being operated in traditional mode in domestic properties. This includes, for example, premises ceasing to exist through demolition or reclassification, as well as suppliers not currently operating smart meters in smart mode when a consumer switches. Some energy suppliers are not yet offering smart services.</p><p> </p><p>However, some suppliers already operate smart meters they have gained upon switching in smart mode. We are encouraging industry parties to enable more consumers to retain their smart services upon switching.</p><p> </p><p>Work is underway to make SMETS1 smart meters interoperable between energy suppliers, through enrolment in to the Data and Communication Company’s system.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720921/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T13:39:05.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720921/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720921/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will make an estimate of the number of SMETS1s that are not in operation due to problems with their interoperability.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","70617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720922","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-20","<p>No. Smart meters complying with the first version of the technical specifications (SMETS1) are delivering real benefits to consumers and have helped the industry prepare for the main installation stage of the roll-out. Work is underway to make SMETS1 smart meters interoperable between energy suppliers, through enrolment in to the DCC’s system.</p><p> </p><p>Consumers with smart meters are having a positive experience and saving energy. Research by Populus for Smart Energy GB, published in February 2017, found that eight in ten (81 per cent) of those with smart meters would recommend them to others.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720922/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T16:33:59.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720922/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720922/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will suspend the roll out of SMETS1s until problems with interoperability have been resolved; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","70618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720923","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-20","<p>The Data and Communications Company (DCC) has consulted on options for ‘enrolling’ SMETS1 meters into its system. DCC is considering stakeholders’ responses and will submit a report to Government on options for enrolment later this year. The cost and benefits of enrolment will depend on which option is pursued and Government will take into account value for money when assessing the options.</p><p> </p><p>It should be noted that the 2016 cost benefit analysis has already made allowance for the plan to enrol and adopt SMETS1 meters into the DCC.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720923/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T13:31:05.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720923/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720923/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will make an estimate of the costs of the Data Communications Company enrolling up to 8 million SMETS1s meters.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","70619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720924","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-25","<p>I refer my hon. Friend to the Public Land for Housing Programme Annual Report published in February 2017.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/592919/170124_PSL_Annual_Report_FINAL_for_publication.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/592919/170124_PSL_Annual_Report</a></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720924/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-25T16:55:13.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720924/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720924/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to paragraphs 1.296 and 1.297 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, what progress his Department has made by estimated capacity of land sold since March 2016 in identifying and disposing of land to meet the Government's commitment.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Prisk","Hertford and Stortford","Mr Mark Prisk","70671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720925","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-20","<p>The Government announced £730m of support for offshore wind and other less established renewable electricity generation technologies in Budget 2016. This funding will go towards projects beginning from 2021 onwards, which will receive a share of this annual budget for the duration of their 15-year contracts.</p><p>Allocation of the first tranche of this support, totalling £290m, began in November last year and projects receiving this support will be announced later this year. The remainder of the support is expected to be allocated before 2020.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720925/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T08:55:18.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720925/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720925/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Wind Power: Seas and Oceans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what his Department's policy is on (a) maintaining and (b) increasing financial support for the offshore wind sector in the next five years.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","70665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720926","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-20","<p>Investment in offshore wind capacity supports many jobs in both Scotland and the rest of the UK. A BIS report published in 2015, ‘The size and performance of the UK low-carbon economy’, estimated that 13,700 jobs in the UK were supported by offshore wind in 2013.</p><p>Recent announcements of supply chain investments and contract awards include CS Wind, 3 Sun Group and Bi-Fab in Scotland, and JDR Cables, Siemens, Granada Material Handling and Harland &amp; Wolff in the rest of the UK.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720926/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T08:54:33.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720926/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720926/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Wind Power: Seas and Oceans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent assessment he has made of the benefits to (a) Scotland and (b) the UK of investment in offshore wind capacity.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","70666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720927","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>Government has awarded £56m to Leeds City Region from the Local Growth Fund for a range of capital grants for SMEs. To date 407 grants have been awarded from the Business Growth Programme, with 70% going to businesses in the manufacturing sector. 42 of these grants, totalling £2.4m, have been awarded to SMEs in the manufacturing sector in Calderdale.</p><p> </p><p>In February this year we announced a £400m Northern Powerhouse Investment Fund (NPIF), aimed at boosting the North of England’s economy and helping the region’s businesses realise their growth potential.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720927/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T11:14:26.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720927/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720927/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Manufacturing Industries: Calderdale","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to support the manufacturing sector in Calderdale.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","70585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720928","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-20","<p>The headline net benefit of the rollout estimated in the 2016 Cost Benefit Analysis is broadly similar to the previous assessment published in 2014. However, there have been significant movements in the composition of benefits beneath the headline figure from updated assumptions and methodological adjustments. As such, it is not meaningful to consider one change in isolation. The 2016 CBA provides an overview of changes to analysis since the 2014 Impact Assessment (Table 2-2 on p.15 of Part I of the CBA).</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720928/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T16:27:27.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720928/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720928/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 29 March 2017 to Question 68881, what proportion of the initially projected benefits of the smart meter rollout is the £1,548 million reduction in benefits, as reported in the 2016 Cost Benefit Analysis.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","70620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720929","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-20","<p>As at 10/04/2017, The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) employed the following numbers on a contract:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Question</p></td><td><p>Headcount</p></td><td><p>%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>a) Full-time permanent staff</p></td><td><p>2663</p></td><td><p>87.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>b) Part-time permanent staff</p></td><td><p>292</p></td><td><p>9.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>c) Less than 2 years duration</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>0.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>d) Agency basis</p></td><td><p>89</p></td><td><p>2.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>e) Zero-hours contract</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p>*Excludes any staff member where BEIS has an agreement rather than a contract - ie loan/secondment in or contracts for service/work package. Headcount includes all staff who are currently inactive (parental leave, loan/secondment out, career break) where the individual still holds a contract with the department.</p></td></tr></tbody></table></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720929/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T10:28:09.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720929/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720929/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many and what proportion of staff employed by his Department are employed on a contract which is (a) full-time permanent, (b) part-time permanent, (c) for less than two years' duration, (d) on an agency basis and (e) zero-hours.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","70600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720930","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>Carbon Capture and Storage (CCS) issues are the responsibility of the Clean Electricity Directorate in the Department.</p><p>Since 2015, the Government has allocated up to approximately £11 million on a range of carbon capture projects supporting research and development in CO<sub>2</sub> storage, carbon capture technologies and CCS feasibility studies.</p><p>The following current projects will be completed in 2017:</p><ul><li><em>Assessing the potential of CO2 utilisation in the UK. </em>Contract value: £75,000;</li><li><em>CO2 transport and storage: review of business models (Phase 1). </em>Contract value: £20,000;</li><li><em>Assessing the cost reduction potential and competitiveness of novel (next generation) UK carbon capture technology. </em>Contract Value: £225,000.</li></ul><p> </p><p>Additionally, the Government Energy Entrepreneurs Fund has funded approximately £1.6 million in support to innovative carbon capture technologies. Phase 5 of this Fund opened on 30 October 2016 with a budget of up to £9 million, which CCS projects were able to apply for. Phase 5 is currently going through the project selection process and the winners will be announced in due course. Further information can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/energy-entrepreneurs-fund-phase-5" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/energy-entrepreneurs-fund-phase-5</a></p><p>The UK has also contracted with the EU to provide €5.5m to the ACT (Accelerating CCS Technologies) Co-fund project. Full details can be found at <a href="http://www.act-ccs.eu/" target="_blank">http://www.act-ccs.eu/</a>.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720930/answer",,,,,"70889","2017-04-24T16:29:43.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720930/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720930/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what projects and activities are being carried out on carbon capture and storage in his Department overseen by the Office for Carbon Capture and Storage.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","70557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720931","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>It is important that consumers are confident they can find the best deals on price comparison websites.</p><p>Currently all energy switching sites accredited to the Ofgem Confidence Code need to provide a comparison of all tariffs available across the market, as a default, regardless of whether the switching site has a commercial arrangement in place with the supplier.</p><p>Following a recommendation by the Competition and Markets Authority, Ofgem launched a consultation on changes to the Confidence Code so that price comparison sites could show, as a default, only those tariffs for which it receives commission, provided it also includes clear and easy access to a whole of market comparison.</p><p>Ofgem is due to publish its decision on the consultation shortly.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720931/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T13:01:21.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720931/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720931/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Energy: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to review the efficacy of energy switching sites.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","70572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720932","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-04-25","<p>Each council’s proposed allocation of the £300 million discretionary relief fund is published here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/discretionary-business-rates-relief-scheme" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/discretionary-business-rates-relief-scheme</a></p><p>Councils will determine how this funding is allocated across businesses in their area.</p><p>Jarrow constituency falls within South Tyneside council. South Tyneside council will receive an allocation of £374,650 over the period 2017-18 to 2020-21. Councils in the North East will receive a total allocation of £7,901,668.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720932/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-25T15:03:04.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720932/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720932/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-04-13","Non-domestic Rates: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to paragraph 3.16 of the Spring Budget 2017, how much of the £300 million discretionary relief fund to provide support for businesses facing significant increases in bills from the English business rates system will be allocated to businesses in (a) Jarrow constituency, (b) South Tyneside and (c) the North East.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","70529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720933","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-21","<p>The national data and communications infrastructure operated by the Data and Communications Company (DCC) is now live, enabling energy suppliers to install and operate SMETS2 meters on its systems. Suppliers are currently carrying out end to end testing using their own internal systems, the DCC, and their selected SMETS2 meters and will commence their rollout of SMETS2 meters as soon has their individual testing is complete.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720933/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-21T10:08:45.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720933/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720933/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when the roll out of SMETS2s will begin.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","70525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720934","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>There is no link in our assessments between the change in benefits mentioned in the question and the interoperability of SMETS1 meters</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720934/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T14:31:20.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720934/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720934/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 29 March 2017 to Question 68881, how much of the additional £1.548 million reduction in benefits, as reported in the 2016 Cost Benefit Analysis, is related to the problems of interoperability of SMETS1s.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","70526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720935","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>I cannot comment on which grace period might be applicable to the Bryn Blaen wind farm as this is a commercial matter for the operator. Ofgem will assess whether a station meets the conditions of the relevant grace period at the point at which the station submits a full application for accreditation.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720935/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T12:59:27.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720935/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720935/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Wind Power: Powys","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, which grace period deadline would apply to Bryn Blaen Wind Farm in Powys under the Renewables Obligation support scheme.","false","Biography information for Glyn Davies","Montgomeryshire","Glyn Davies","70513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720936","Department for Education","false","2017-04-21","<p>The Skills Funding Agency and Education Funding Agency merged on 1 April 2017 to form the Education and Skills Funding Agency (ESFA). As a result of this change, the Skills Funding Agency Advisory Board ceased to exist on 1 April 2017. A new board will be set up to oversee the work of the new agency, and members will be appointed in due course. Arrangements for this will be published by the Department for Education in the new agency’s Framework Document as soon as possible. This document will be available on GOV.UK.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720936/answer",,,,,"70718 ; 70862","2017-04-21T11:52:59.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720936/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720936/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-04-13","Skills Funding Agency: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many applications the board of the Skills Funding Agency received during its last intake.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720937","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-04-24","<p>The number of reports lodged on the Director Conduct Reporting Service (DCRS) each quarter since the service went live on 6 April 2016 is as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Quarter</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total DCRS Reports</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>6 April 2016 – 30 June 2016</p></td><td><p>239*</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 July 2016 – 30 September 2016</p></td><td><p>3,412</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 October 2016 – 31 December 2016</p></td><td><p>3,810</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 January 2017 – 31 March 2017</p></td><td><p>4,081</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>11,542</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><em>*The initial low figure is because office holders were only required to use the DCRS for new appointments from 6 April and have 3 months to report.</em></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720937/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T11:14:40.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720937/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720937/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-04-13","Directors: Conduct","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many reports have been lodged on the Director Conduct Reporting Service under section 7A of the Company Directors Disqualification Act 1986 in each quarter since that service commenced.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","70480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720938","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-25","<p>Following the formation of the Department for International Trade (DIT) we have been reviewing and developing our processes for collating this data. This has now been finalised and we are working to collate data for the whole department. This has involved working across multiple departmental systems due to the Machinery of Government changes creating DIT. In line with Cabinet Office guidance, the Department aims to start publishing later in 2017 and this will include backdated information.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720938/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-25T09:25:36.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720938/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720938/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-13","Department for International Trade: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, for what reason his Department has not published spend greater than £25,000 since July 2016; and when that information will be published.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","70518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720939","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-21","<p>The UK has a strong history of protecting workers’ rights. We are working with departments across Whitehall to determine our approach to future trade agreements, including with respect to workers’ rights.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720939/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-21T10:47:41.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720939/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720939/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-13","Trade Agreements: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many reports he has commissioned to seek advice on free trade agreement provisions and workers' rights.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","70569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720940","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-21","<p>We are working closely with departments across Whitehall to determine our approach to future trade agreements, including with respect to environmental protection, informed by relevant evidence and advice.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720940/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-21T10:46:28.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720940/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720940/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-13","Trade Agreements: Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many reports he has commissioned to seek advice on free trade agreement provisions and environmental protection.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","70570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720941","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-24","<p>Data on the number of companies that export goods from West Yorkshire and Calderdale are not available. The number of companies in Yorkshire and the Humber exporting goods to non-EU countries since 2010 is available in the HMRC Regional Trade Statistics.</p><p> </p><p>Data for 2013 to 2016:</p><p><a href="https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/RTS/RTS%20Releases/RTS_Q4_2016.xls" target="_blank">https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/RTS/RTS%20Releases/RTS_Q4_2016.xls</a> (Table 3, CEp)</p><p> </p><p>Data for 2010 to 2012:</p><p><a href="https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/RTS/RTS%20Releases/RtsQ42012.xls" target="_blank">https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/RTS/RTS%20Releases/RtsQ42012.xls</a> (Table 3, CE)</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720941/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T15:24:07.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720941/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720941/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-13","Exports: West Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many companies in (a) West Yorkshire and (b) Calderdale exported goods or services to non-EU countries in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","70582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720942","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-20","<p>During the period 2005-2014, ONS statistics show that services represented on average 84% of UK exports to Liechtenstein, within which financial services are likely to have made a significant contribution.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720942/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T14:08:23.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720942/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720942/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-13","Exports: Liechtenstein","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 23 March 2017 to Question 69047, which UK economic sectors have contributed to the 40 per cent growth in UK exports of goods and services to Liechtenstein between 2005 and 2014.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","70635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720943","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-20","<p>The Department for International Trade Regularly meets with businesses and representatives from across the UK, including the agricultural sector, and will continue to do so.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720943/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T15:08:25.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720943/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720943/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-13","National Farmers Union","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many meetings officials of his Department have had with the National Farmers' Union since 1 January 2017.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","70659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720944","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-20","<p>The UK Government is firmly committed to delivering the sustainable development goals both at home and around the world. We are working with departments across Whitehall to determine our approach to future trade agreements, including with respect to sustainable development, informed by relevant evidence and advice.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720944/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T15:37:17.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720944/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720944/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-13","Trade Agreements: Sustainable Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many reports he has commissioned to seek advice on free trade agreement provisions and sustainable development goals.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","70661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720945","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015 were conducted before the establishment of the Department for International Trade (DIT) and at this time UK Trade and Investment was part of the then Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) and the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO). When DIT was set up there was no transfer of land assets from BIS or FCO and hence DIT do not own any land or property assets that could be sold.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720945/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-25T09:03:31.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720945/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720945/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-13","Department for International Trade: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, with reference to paragraphs 1.296 and 1.297 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, what progress his Department has made by estimated capacity of land sold since March 2016 in identifying and disposing of land to meet the Government's commitment.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Prisk","Hertford and Stortford","Mr Mark Prisk","70682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720946","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-20","<p>The UK has a strong history of defending human rights and continues to be at the forefront of human rights protections. We are working with departments across Whitehall to determine our approach to future trade agreements, including with respect to human rights, informed by relevant evidence and advice.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720946/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T14:27:53.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720946/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720946/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-13","Trade Agreements: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many reports he has commissioned to seek advice on free trade agreement provisions and human rights.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","70660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720947","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-20","<p>In their recent meeting, the President of the Philippines and my Rt. Hon Friend, the Secretary of State for International Trade had a wide ranging discussion that included illegal drugs, in the context of the importance of the rule of law, adhering to international obligations as well as the implications on international trade arrangements.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720947/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T14:15:43.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720947/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720947/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-13","Drugs: Philippines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether he made representations during his recent meeting with the President of the Philippines on the Government of Philippines' policy on tackling illegal drugs.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","70775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720948","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-24","<p>The number and proportion of people employed by the Department for International Trade in the categories requested are shown in the table below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Number</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Proportion</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Full time permanent contract</p></td><td><p>2348</p></td><td><p>75.1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Part time permanent contract</p></td><td><p>410</p></td><td><p>13.1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Contract for less than 2 years</p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>0.5%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Agency contract</p></td><td><p>353</p></td><td><p>11.3%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Zero hours contract</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3126</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>100%</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720948/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T14:49:24.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720948/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720948/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-13","Department for International Trade: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many and what proportion of staff employed by his Department are employed on a contract which is (a) full-time permanent, (b) part-time permanent, (c) for less than two years' duration, (d) on an agency basis and (e) zero-hours.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","70468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720949","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-20","<p>My Rt. hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade has met with Meurig Raymond, President of the National Farmers’ Union, as well as local representatives.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720949/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T15:18:01.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720949/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720949/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-13","National Farmers Union","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether he has met the National Farmers' Union since 1 January 2017.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","70345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720950","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Commercial Function within the Department for International Trade has a wider remit than Procurement Management therefore it is not possible to disaggregate this spending.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720950/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-25T15:45:14.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720950/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720950/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-13","Department for International Trade: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what estimate he has made of his Department's spending on procurement management since its formation.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720951","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-24","<p>The Cabinet Office defines consultancy spend as the provision to management of objective advice relating to strategy, structure, management or operations of an organisation. The definition does not include the delivery of solutions or contingent labour. The Department for International Trade (DIT) currently has one exemption to Cabinet Office Controls on consultancy spend relating to the provision of strategic advice and implementation guidance for the UK Trade and Investment transformation programme.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720951/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T15:15:08.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720951/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720951/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-13","Department for International Trade: Management Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how much his Department has spent on the services of management consultants since its creation.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","70225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720952","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-24","<p>The UK Government is firmly committed to delivering the UN Sustainable Development Goals both at home and around the world. The Department for International Trade has met with a variety of civil society organisations. We are working closely with them across a range of areas, including sustainable development, as we develop our approach to trade policy.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720952/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-24T08:12:49.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720952/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720952/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-13","Department for International Trade: Third Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, with which civil society organisations officials of his Department have met to discuss sustainable development and trade since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","70217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720953","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-25","<p>The Department for International Trade is working with the Department for Environment, Food &amp; Rural Affairs on relevant areas of trade policy and have met with, and continue to meet, a variety of civil society organisations. We are working closely with them across a range of areas, including environmental protection, as we develop our approach to trade policy.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720953/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-25T08:39:29.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720953/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720953/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-13","Department for International Trade: Third Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, with which civil society organisations officials of his Department have met to discuss environmental protection and trade since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","70218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720954","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-25","<p>The UK is a long standing supporter of fair trade. Ministers and officials meet with a wide range of stakeholders, including civil society organisations as part of the normal course of business. These discussions cover a wider range of issues, including fair trade.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720954/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-25T11:44:12.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720954/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720954/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-13","Department for International Trade: Third Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, with which civil society organisations officials of his Department have met to discuss fair trade since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","70219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720955","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-20","<p>The UK has a strong history in defending human rights and continues to be at the forefront of human rights protections. The Department for International Trade has met with a variety of civil society organisations. We are working closely with them across a range of areas, including human rights, as we develop our approach to trade policy.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720955/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-20T15:31:10.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720955/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720955/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-13","Department for International Trade: Third Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, which civil society organisations officials of his Department have met to discuss human rights and trade since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","70283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720956","Department for International Trade","false","2017-04-25","<table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> </strong> <strong>Criterion</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Lead Department</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Criterion 1</p></td><td><p>FCO</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Criterion 2</p></td><td><p>FCO</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Criterion 3</p></td><td><p>FCO</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Criterion 4</p></td><td><p>FCO</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Criterion 5</p></td><td><p>MOD</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Criterion 6</p></td><td><p>FCO</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Criterion 7</p></td><td><p>MOD and FCO</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Criterion 8</p></td><td><p>DfID</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Further details are set out in Annex A of the United Kingdom Strategic Export Controls Annual Report 2015. Although this publication predates the creation of the Department for International Trade, the lead departments as set out above are unchanged. (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/uk-annual-report-on-strategic-export-controls-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/uk-annual-report-on-strategic-export-controls-2015</a>).</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720956/answer",,,,,,"2017-04-25T13:38:17.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720956/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/720956/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-04-13","Arms Trade: Export Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, which Government department has the lead responsibility for assessing each of the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","70268"
